Types of integrations we can have with influencers
Mentions ‚Äì a ‚Äúshoutout‚Äù style partnership, where you talk about the brand for anywhere from 30-60 seconds.
Integrations ‚Äì a longer ‚Äúshoutout‚Äù style partnership where you talk about the brand for anywhere from 90 seconds to 2 minutes. The integration should be relevant to the video and talking about the brand should feel more natural to the viewer.  
Dedicated Videos ‚Äì  an entire video about the brand or the product that they‚Äôre sent to you. 
Shorts ‚Äì a brand sponsors a Short instead of a full video.





Factors Influencing Creator Pricing
Subscriber Count & Engagement: Larger channels with more engaged audiences can command higher prices. 
Niche and Audience Value: Niches like technology and finance may have higher CPMs due to high-value audiences. 
Video Length and Placement: Longer integrations or integrations in prominent spots may cost more. 
Content Type: Creators can charge a flat fee for the video or use pricing models like Cost Per Mille (CPM) or Cost Per View (CPV). 
Negotiation: Brands and creators negotiate the terms, and the first price quoted by the creator can serve as a starting point for negotiation. 
How to Determine Your Collaboration Rate
Calculate Your Average Views and CPM: Use your YouTube Analytics to find out how many average views your videos receive. 
Decide on a Pricing Model:
Flat Fee: A set price for the sponsored content. 
CPM (Cost Per Mille): A payment for every thousand views the sponsored video receives. 
CPV (Cost Per View): A set amount for each view of the sponsored advertisement. 
Consider Your Value: Be professional and provide clear justifications for your pricing based on your audience's value and the effort involved



